{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/luxury-symbols","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h2>Inspiration</h2>\n<p>My unnecessary, but frequent use of the phrase \"and/or\" when not taking got me thinking about other similar colloqiual phrases that don't have symbolic shorthand representations.  Of course we have the ampersand and, in technical settings, the bar <code class=\"language-text\">|</code> used to denote \"or,\" but after getting to thinking (and realizing I already struggle to differentiate my <code class=\"language-text\">I/l/|</code>'s, due to horrific handwriting), I decided I ought to develop additional shorthand symbols to convey those phrases.  After some further searching and contmpation I also stumbled upon the perfect example of one such symbol: the interrobang: <code class=\"language-text\">‽</code> which is pretty self-explanatory.</p>\n<p>Before opening up illustrator and getting carried away by intricate symbols, I decided I needed to lay down some criteria to keep the symbols pragmatic:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>They needed to be easy to write (sorry Hanzi),</li>\n<li>I needed to be able to draw the symbol faster than I could write the representated phrase, e.g. <code>∧/∨</code> is barely faster than simply writing <code class=\"language-text\">and/or</code></li>\n<li>The symbol needs to be relatively easy to decipher, as with the interrobang.</li>\n<li>They still need to look cool, yo!</li>\n</ul>\n<p> With no further adeu, I present my shorthand:</p>\n<h2>And / or</h2>\n<p> <svg id=\"Layer_1\" data-name=\"Layer 1\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 63.5 78.28\" height=\"50\"><defs><style>.cls-1{fill:none;stroke:#000;stroke-miterlimit:10;stroke-width:8px;}</style></defs><path d=\"M500.32,670c-6.15,0-11.13-1.6-14.79-4.76s-5.71-7.81-5.71-13.52a17.76,17.76,0,0,1,3.48-11,29.88,29.88,0,0,1,8.37-6.94l-.4-.43a25.18,25.18,0,0,1-4.33-6.18,16,16,0,0,1-1.53-6.83,14.16,14.16,0,0,1,4.75-11.12c3-2.67,